  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "intro", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# Task 12: Advanced Exercises\n\nExtend your BERT implementation with advanced features!"]},
  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "hf-compat", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Exercise 1: HuggingFace Compatibility\n\nMake your BERT compatible with HuggingFace transformers."]},
  {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "id": "hf-impl", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["# Implement a HuggingFace-compatible BERT\nfrom transformers import BertConfig, BertModel, BertTokenizer\n\n# Use your architecture with HF config\nconfig = BertConfig(\n    vocab_size=30000,\n    hidden_size=256,\n    num_hidden_layers=4,\n    num_attention_heads=4,\n    intermediate_size=512,\n    hidden_dropout_prob=0.1,\n    attention_probs_dropout_prob=0.1\n)\n\n# This creates a BERT model with the same architecture\nhf_bert = BertModel(config)\n\n# Load pretrained weights (if you have them)\n# hf_bert = BertModel.from_pretrained('path/to/your/model')\n\nprint(f\"HuggingFace BERT: {sum(p.numel() for p in hf_bert.parameters()):,} parameters\")"]},
  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "roberta", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Exercise 2: RoBERTa Variation\n\nRoBERTa removes NSP and trains longer with more data.\n\n```python\n# Changes from BERT:\n# 1. No NSP loss (just MLM)\n# 2. Dynamic masking\n# 3. Larger batch sizes\n# 4. Longer training\n```"]},
  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "albert", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Exercise 3: ALBERT (A Lite BERT)\n\nALBERT uses parameter sharing and factorized embeddings.\n\n```python\n# Key changes:\n# 1. Factorized embedding: separate small embedding + projection\n# 2. Cross-layer parameter sharing\n# 3. Sentence Order Prediction (SOP) instead of NSP\n```"]},
  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "customization", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Exercise 4: Custom Extensions\n\nTry these customizations:\n\n1. **Different activation functions**: GELU → SwiGLU, GeGLU\n2. **Attention mechanisms**: Add relative positional bias\n3. **Layer norm**: Pre-norm vs post-norm\n4. **Pooling**: Mean pooling, attention-weighted pooling\n5. **Knowledge distillation**: Train a smaller student model"]},
  {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null,
<parameter name="id": "pre-norm", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["# Pre-norm vs Post-norm comparison\n\n# Post-norm (original BERT): LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x))\nclass PostNormBlock(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model, num_heads):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(d_model, num_heads, batch_first=True)\n        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.ffn = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(d_model, d_model*4), nn.GELU(), nn.Linear(d_model*4, d_model))\n        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        \n    def forward(self, x):\n        x = self.norm1(x + self.attn(x, x, x)[0])  # Post-norm\n        x = self.norm2(x + self.ffn(x))             # Post-norm\n        return x\n\n# Pre-norm: x + Sublayer(LayerNorm(x))\nclass PreNormBlock(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model, num_heads):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(d_model, num_heads, batch_first=True)\n        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.ffn = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(d_model, d_model*4), nn.GELU(), nn.Linear(d_model*4, d_model))\n        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        \n    def forward(self, x):\n        x = x + self.attn(self.norm1(x), self.norm1(x), self.norm1(x))[0]  # Pre-norm\n        x = x + self.ffn(self.norm2(x))  # Pre-norm\n        return x\n\nprint(\"Pre-norm often leads to more stable training!\")"]},
  {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "conclusion", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## 🎉 Congratulations!\n\nYou've completed the BERT from Scratch project!\n\n### What you learned:\n- ✅ PyTorch fundamentals\n- ✅ Self-attention & Multi-head attention\n- ✅ Transformer encoder architecture\n- ✅ Positional embeddings\n- ✅ BERT embeddings & encoder\n- ✅ MLM + NSP pretraining\n- ✅ Classification finetuning\n- ✅ Question answering\n- ✅ Model serving with FastAPI\n- ✅ Production optimization\n\n### Next steps:\n1. Train on real data\n2. Experiment with hyperparameters\n3. Try different model sizes\n4. Explore other transformer variants (GPT, T5, etc.)\n\nHappy learning! 🚀"]}
